T1  - Increasing returns, dynamic stability, and international trade
AU  - Panagariya, Arvind
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
SP  - 43
EP  - 63
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90060-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900607
AB  - A simple two-country, two-good model in which economies of scale form the basis of international trade is presented. It is shown that the larger country exports the good characterized by increasing returns and imports the good subject to constant returns. A key feature of the paper is a comprehensive stability analysis. It turns out that a normal output-price response is necessary for D-stability. Furthermore, the Marshall-Lerner condition must be satisfied in terms of the short-run import-demand elasticities for local dynamic stability. Finally, if international factor mobility is permitted, ‘cross-hauling’ of specific factors may be observed.
ER  - 

