UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900632
AB  - An intertemporal model of OPEC and two large-country oil importers is used to show that asymmetries between importers cause oil price changes to alter the terms of trade between them in systematic ways. For example, differences in oil dependence, marginal propensities to save, international debt positions, factor substitutability, trade in capital goods and wage setting behavior can all influence the final-goods terms of trade between oil importers in predictable ways when oil prices change.
