DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(86)90068-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199686900681
AB  - A country with significant foreign investment can be immiserized by growth of its labor force because this increases the payments that have to be made to foreign investors. We show that this occurs when the elasticity of supply of foreign capital and the elasticity of substitution between labor and capital in the host country are low. We relate this phenomenon to Bhagwati's general analysis of immiserizing growth and identify several new sources of immiserization that can arise from the interaction of the Bhagwati/Johnson mechanisms and international investment.
